turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Ohh, hello.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Hello. I'm Doctor <UNSURE>Geraghty</UNSURE>. Ohh, <UNIN/> sorry. <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>. Can I take your, full name, date of birth, and, your home address please?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, yeah it's uh, <UNIN/>. Um, and, five, um, Kings Place.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: And are you in a, uh, and your date of birth?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, it's the twentieth, of the fourth, nineteen ninety.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And are you in a private place you can have a confidential consultation today?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yes, I am.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: What can I do for you today?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, I've got a really bad headache, had it for about a day now.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, and can you just tell me about, how it started? What were you doing when it came on?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, yeah, just ever since yesterday morning, since I woke up really. Um, just yeah, kind of throbbing headache, haven't really wanted to leave the house much since then.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, and whereabouts in your head is the pain?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, mainly on the left side.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. What does it feel like?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, it just, kind of feels like it's throbbing, it's quite intense, sort of comes and goes. Um, yeah, quite sensitive to light, um, but yeah, quite painful.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: K and <UNIN/>. When, when you say it comes and goes, does it completely go away?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, just kind of fades, so it's still there a little bit but, it kind of gets more or less, severe.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And any, any other symptoms that you've had, any problems with your eyes, or your eyesight?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no, not at all.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Any abnormal smells or tastes?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Any, any nausea, vomiting?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no, no, been feeling fine actually.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: And have you been eating and drinking OK?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah, yeah, <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And, normally, do you get any headaches?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no not really, it's not something I've, ever had before.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And, has it occurred at a particular term in your menstrual cycle?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, no, not particularly, <UNIN/> <UNSURE>and</UNSURE> my period was about a week ago.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Right, OK. And how we're you the before it came on? Have you had any other symptoms, like feeling feverish, <UNIN/>, runny nose, sore ears?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No, not really any sort of, cold symptoms, I seemed OK the day before.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And, at the moment, how are you feeling?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, it's still pretty bad. Um, yeah, <UNSURE>still the</UNSURE> kind of throbbing, yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Have you had any changes in your skin?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No, <UNSURE>skin feeling</UNSURE> fine.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Have you checked your temperature at all?  Have you got a thermometer at home?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, I haven't. Um, I don't feel like I'm feverish, but I haven't checked.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: And any problems with weakness, tingling, numbness in your arms or legs?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No, not at all.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: And what have you been doing since it came on? Have you been able to go to work, or have you been at home?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, taken some painkillers, mainly been at home. Um, yeah just kind of, kind of seems to be worse, when I'm in a light room or like sunlight. So I've kind of just been staying in as much as possible.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. Does it get worse with any position that you're <UNSURE>on</UNSURE>? Is it worse when you lie flat, or when you bend forward?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, no, think I've generally been lying down, <UNSURE>seems to</UNSURE> be better that way.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Any problems if you cough or sneeze?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no, but I haven't really got a cough or anything.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And can you just tell me a bit about, your medical history in the past? Have you had any significant medical problems? Any hospital admissions, operations, <UNSURE>something</UNSURE> like that?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no, not recently, nothing.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Do you take any medication?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no, just contraception.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: And which contraception do you take?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, Microgynon, <UNIN/> pill.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>When</UNSURE> did you start that one?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, about six years ago.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Do you get any side effects from it?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, not really, um, no, not too much.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And, anyone in your family had any medical problems?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, my mum had, <UNSURE>uh</UNSURE>, high blood pressure, and she's got a history of migraines. Um, but <UNSURE>it's</UNSURE> not really affected me before.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: And have you had your blood pressure checked <UNIN/> recently?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, I haven't actually, no.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Have you had it checked, when you've had the <UNIN/>, repeat prescription done?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah, yeah, so uh, probably about six months ago.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Do you know if there's been any problems with it?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, it's always been fine I think.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. Um, and whereabouts, whereabouts do you live at the moment? You've given me your, address. <UNSURE>Do</UNSURE>, who do you live with at home?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, just with housemates, um, just friends.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And do you drink much alcohol day-to-day?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, I'd say a normal amount, um, probably, you know, a few drinks at the weekend.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And do you smoke?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Do you take any other drugs of any sort?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: No.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Um. So, <UNIN/>, what, what tablets did you say you've been taking already? <UNSURE>Yeah</UNSURE>.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Sorry?

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: What tablets have you been taking already, for it?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, just Paracetamol. Um, I'm allergic to Aspirin, so I haven't been taking that.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: What happens when you get <UNSURE>a</UNSURE>, when you take Aspirin?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, I just feel really sick.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. And have you ever, taken any, non-steroidal anti-inflammatories, like Ibuprofen, Naproxen, anything like that?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Um, I have in the past, I haven't been taking it, last few days.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. Um, so, this headache is new to you, and you've, you've not had regular headaches before?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: What I would, suggest is, taking, uh, um, some anti-inflammatories, along with the Paracetamol.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: OK.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNSURE>Um, as a</UNSURE>. Uh, you said you're eating OK?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yeah, yeah, fine.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: I mean it, from the sounds of it, it does, sound quite like a migraine, but obviously <UNSURE>if you</UNSURE> had no history of that, in the past.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Um, and is anything changed recently, or any, anything you've done recently might've, triggered it?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, not that I can think of, um, may have been a bit stressed out at work, that kind of thing, but <UNIN/>.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <INAUDIBLE_SPEECH/>

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Yeah. Um, well that would be the first thing to do, is to take some anti-inflammatories along with the Paracetamol. Make sure you're really well hydrated.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Um, and, see how that goes, and if it, if it isn't settling, or it's getting worse, or you get any other change in your headache. Um, or you're unwell with it, with a high temperature, then we would certainly need to speak to you.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Straight away about that. The other thing is if you, if you're getting persistent, um, headaches, or headaches associated with your menstrual cycle, or certain things seem to trigger these headaches.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Then, it, it would be worth, having a further discussion about it, to see whether we can, work out if we can help <UNSURE>the</UNSURE>, that longer-term.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: OK, brilliant, thank you.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Um, I would, try and arrange to get your blood pressure checked, if you haven't had it checked for a while.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: Uh, <UNSURE>and</UNSURE>, thing to do <UNSURE>is</UNSURE> to have a thermometer at home, so you <UNSURE>can</UNSURE> make sure that your temperature's OK.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: OK, sure.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yep.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: If you have a raised temperature or, your headache's just getting <UNSURE>worse, or</UNSURE> you develop any rashes or anything like that. Then we'd need to speak to you straight away.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Yep, OK, that's brilliant. OK, so I'll take some Ibuprofen and I'll um, hopefully, be a bit better in a day or two then, so yeah.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK, so, have you got any other questions?

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Uh, no, that was it today.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: OK. OK then, we'll, we'll, we'll, um, speak to you again.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: OK, brilliant. Thanks <UNSURE>so</UNSURE> much.

turns.speaker: DOCTOR
turns.text: <UNIN/>, <UNSURE>very</UNSURE> much. Bye.

turns.speaker: PATIENT
turns.text: Bye.
